---
title: Open-source electronic conspicuity for general aviation
description: skyBlip makes your aircraft, microlight or glider visible to others and displays surrounding traffic, on your tablet or your panel display. Open source and affordable.
---

<header class="hero">
  <div class="wordmark wordmark-hero"><span class="quiet">sky</span><span class="loud">Bl<span class="glyph">&#305;<svg class="overlay overlay-blip" viewBox="0 0 40 40" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="20" cy="34" r="5.5" fill="#FF4F1F"/><path d="M10 25 A14 14 0 0 1 30 25" fill="none" stroke="#FF4F1F" stroke-width="3.5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity=".65"/><path d="M4 15 A22 22 0 0 1 36 15" fill="none" stroke="#FF4F1F" stroke-width="3.5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity=".3"/></svg></span>p</span></div>
  <p class="tagline">Open-source electronic conspicuity for general aviation.</p>
  <p class="lede">
    Flying VFR, everyone watches for the others through the canopy. skyBlip
    adds a second pair of eyes: a small device that announces your position
    by radio and receives everyone else&rsquo;s. Nearby traffic shows up on
    the skyBlip&rsquo;s own screen, on your tablet or on your panel display,
    and an alarm warns you when an aircraft converges.
  </p>
</header>

<section>
  <h2 class="kicker">In the aircraft</h2>
  <div class="wordmark wordmark-section"><span class="quiet">sky</span><span class="loud">Bl<span class="glyph">&#305;<svg class="overlay overlay-blip" viewBox="0 0 40 40" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="20" cy="34" r="5.5" fill="#FF4F1F"/><path d="M10 25 A14 14 0 0 1 30 25" fill="none" stroke="#FF4F1F" stroke-width="3.5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity=".65"/><path d="M4 15 A22 22 0 0 1 36 15" fill="none" stroke="#FF4F1F" stroke-width="3.5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity=".3"/></svg></span>p</span></div>
  <p class="product-tagline">See &amp; be seen.</p>
  <p>A skyBlip makes your aircraft visible to others and displays surrounding traffic.</p>

  <div class="cards">
    <article class="card card-featured">
      <div class="card-featured-body">
      <h3>skyBlip Go <span class="tag">the pocket tracker</span></h3>
      <p>
        A standalone, battery-powered device with nothing to install: it
        slips into a jacket pocket and sits in the cockpit. It transmits your
        position, receives everyone else&rsquo;s (including FLARM-equipped
        gliders), shows a radar on its own screen and alerts on converging
        traffic. Connected over Bluetooth, it
        puts the aircraft around you into the navigation app you already
        use: SDVFR Next, SkyDemon, ForeFlight and the others.
      </p>
      <p class="note">
        Works everywhere, with no infrastructure and no subscription. Under
        skyPost ground coverage, the picture gains the traffic detected from
        the ground (airliners and touring aircraft on ADS-B) plus weather
        (QNH, METAR, TAF).
      </p>
      </div>
      <%= pages_image_tag "skyblip-go-techo.jpg", alt: "skyBlip Go: white device with antenna, skyBlip shown on the e-paper screen" %>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h3>skyBlip Go, on a Stratux <span class="tag">the ADS-L add-on for your Stratux</span></h3>
      <p>
        The same device, plugged into the Stratux USB port, completes it.
        The ADS-L and FLARM traffic it receives joins the Stratux picture
        and shows up in your EFB like the rest. Above all, the Go transmits
        your position: the Stratux lets you see traffic, the skyBlip makes
        you visible.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <h3>skyBlip Panel <span class="tag">for glass cockpits</span></h3>
      <p>
        For aircraft with a glass cockpit: Garmin G3X, Dynon SkyView and
        others. A discreet unit installed behind the panel and powered by the
        aircraft, showing traffic directly on your screen, like a
        factory-fitted traffic source. No extra screen, no subscription.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>

  <p class="note">
    Each skyBlip keeps a track of your flights in its memory. Back on the
    ground, open your browser and connect over Bluetooth: your flights
    download in seconds, with no app and no account.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="kicker">On the ground</h2>
  <div class="wordmark wordmark-section"><span class="quiet">sky</span><span class="loud">P<span class="glyph"><span class="o-ring"></span><svg class="overlay overlay-post" viewBox="-25 -25 50 50" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M-11.8 -18 A21.5 21.5 0 0 1 11.8 -18" fill="none" stroke="#FF4F1F" stroke-width="3.5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity=".65"/><path d="M-15.9 -26 A30.5 30.5 0 0 1 15.9 -26" fill="none" stroke="#FF4F1F" stroke-width="3.5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity=".3"/></svg></span>st</span></div>
  <p class="product-tagline">Received on the ground, relayed in flight.</p>
  <p>
    Airliners and a large share of touring aircraft already announce their
    position over ADS-B. skyPost ground stations receive those announcements,
    add the traffic from online networks such as the Open Glider Network
    (OGN), and rebroadcast the whole picture to the skyBlips in flight. One
    station on a club roof covers the field, the circuit and the
    surroundings; the solar version mounts on a simple mast.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="kicker">The devices</h2>
  <p>
    Two devices to choose from for the aircraft (skyBlip Go, skyBlip Panel)
    and two ground station models (skyPost Helio, skyPost Bridge).
  </p>
  <p><%= link_to_page "devices", class: "cta" %> →</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="kicker">For the technically minded</h2>
  <h3>In short</h3>
  <p>
    skyBlip and skyPost implement <strong>ADS-L</strong>
    (<em><a href="https://www.easa.europa.eu/en/document-library/agency-decisions/ed-decision-2022024r">ADS-L 4 SRD-860, Issue&nbsp;2</a></em>),
    the electronic conspicuity protocol published by EASA for the
    licence-free 868&nbsp;MHz band.
  </p>
  <p>
    ADS-B is neither re-implemented nor
    transmitted on 1090&nbsp;MHz: it is received on the ground by the
    skyPosts, then relayed over ADS-L. The skyPosts
    exchange traffic with the Open Glider Network in both directions.
  </p>
</section>

